Dengue - China (Hong Kong) 19980816.1630
Dengue, imported - China (Hong Kong) 19980513.0942
Date: Sat 25 Aug 2001
From: "Stephen A Berger MD" <mberger@post.tau.ac.il>
Source: The GIDEON Database, Sat 24 Aug 2001 [edited
<http://www.GideonOnline.com>
Background data on dengue in China extracted from the GIDEON database
---------------------------------------------------------------------
Dengue is most common in Guangdong, Guangxi, and Hainan Island. No cases
were reported during 1946 to 1978. Three outbreaks were reported between
1978 and 1983 (21 227 cases in 1979, 443 159 (64 fatal) in 1980, 85 293 in
1983).
China's first epidemic of dengue hemorrhagic fever (DHF) was recorded in
1985. 114 107 cases (case fatality rate = 0.2 per cent) were reported on
Hainan Island in 1986. 127 568 cases of DHF (4792 fatal) were reported
between 1986 and 1990.
Since 1986, outbreaks and sporadic cases have been largely limited to
Guangzhou city, Guangdong Province, and Hainan Island. 112 cases of dengue
were reported from Shaxi District in 1991; 6077 cases were reported in
1995. Dengue was first reported in Fujian Province in 1999 -- both in
humans and mosquitoes.
51 510 cases of DHF (1529 fatal) were reported nationwide in 1988 --
including 5195 with a case fatality rate of 0.38 per cent in Foshan. 37 886
cases (807 fatal) were reported in 1989; 376 (0) in 1990; 902 in 1991; 46
095 in 1992; 359 in 1993; 2 (0) in 1994; 6 114 (0) in 1995; 8 (0) in 1996.
647 cases of dengue (0 fatal) were reported in 1997; 15 in 1998; 1 306 (0
fatal) in 1999.
Reported disease rates for dengue (per 100 000) were 0.0003 in 1994; 0.577
in 1995; 0.0002 in 1996; 0.053 in 1997.
Dengue in Hong Kong: dengue has been a notifiable disease in Hong Kong
since 1994. Five cases (0 fatal) were reported in 1996. Ten cases (0 fatal)
were reported in 1997; 15 in 1998 - 13 imported from South East Asia and 2
from the Indian subcontinent; 5 in 1999; 7 in 2000. _Aedes aegypti_ is not
present in Hong Kong but _Aedes albopictus_ is ubiquitous.
--
Stephen A Berger MD
